        // This forms a new string that is identical to s.
        //
        // The problem statement implies that if k=1 doesn't work, and it's not all same chars,
        // then k=2 is the answer. This is a known property for palindromes.
        // A simple way to achieve k=2 is to cut s into s[0], s.substr(1, n-2), s[n-1].
        // Then reorder as s.substr(1, n-2) + s[0] + s[n-1].
        // This is s.substr(1, n-2) + s[0] + s[0].
        // This new string is a palindrome if s.substr(1, n-2) is a palindrome.
        // Since s is a palindrome, s.substr(1, n-2) is also a palindrome.
        // The new string is s.substr(1, n-2) + s[0] + s[0].
