        // The key insight for the reverse Floyd-Warshall is that when vertex `k` is added,
        // it becomes the *newest* intermediate vertex.
        // So, for any pair of vertices `i` and `j` that are currently active (including `k` itself),
        // their shortest path `dist[i][j]` might be improved by going through `k`.
        // The `dist` matrix at any point stores the shortest paths between all *currently active* vertices,
        // using only *currently active* vertices as intermediates.
        // So, when `k` is added, we need to update `dist[i][j]` for all active `i, j` (including `k`)
        // using `k` as an intermediate.
        // This means the loops should be:
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            if (!active[i]) continue;
            for (int j = 0; j < n; ++j) {
